, devotion and balance. So she travels to Rome, where she learns Italian from handsome, brown-eyed identical twins and gains twenty-five pounds, an ashram in India, where she finds that enlightenment entails getting up in the middle of the night to scrub the temple floor, and Bali where a toothless medicine man of indeterminate age offers her a new path to peace: simply sit still and smile. And slowly happiness begins to creep up on her. 0aElectronic books.2 acloudLibrary403Whole productuhttp://ebook.yourcloudlibrary.com:80/library/dekrook-document_id-oee93z904564nam  22002654  45000010014000000060019000140070015000330080041000480200018000890370012001070400028001190720023001471000023001702450097001932600051002903000011003415203561003526500017039136500048039306500063039786550022040417100017040638560092040808560126041729780812995008m    ||  d |      cr un|||||||||170506s2014||||||||||||s|||||||||||eng||  a9780812995008  aoczfp89  aMnSpTMCLbengcMnSpTMCL  aBIO0260002bisacsh1 aDunham, Lena.4aut10aNot That Kind of GirlbA Young Woman Tells You What She's "Learned"h[electronic resource] :  a[S.l.]:bRandom House Publishing Group,c2014.  a320 p.  a#1&#xA0;NEW YORK TIMES BESTSELLER &#x2022; Includes two new essays! NAMED ONE OF THE TEN BEST BOOKS OF THE YEAR BY MICHIKO KAKUTANI,&#xA0;THE NEW YORK TIMES &#x2022;&#xA0;NAMED ONE OF THE BEST BOOKS OF THE YEAR BY BUZZFEED, THE GLOBE AND MAIL,&#xA0;AND LIBRARY JOURNAL For readers of Nora Ephron, Tina Fey, and David Sedaris, this hilarious, wise, and fiercely candid collection of personal essays establishes Lena Dunham&#x2014;the acclaimed creator, producer, and star of HBO&#x2019;s Girls&#x2014;as one of the most original young talents writing today. &#xA0; In Not That Kind of Girl, Dunham illuminates the experiences that are part of making one&#x2019;s way in the world: falling in love, feeling alone, being ten pounds overweight despite eating only health food, having to prove yourself in a room full of men twice your age, finding true love, and most of all, having the guts to believe that your story is one that deserves to be told. &#xA0; (S2(BTake My Virginity (No Really, Take It)(S3 (Bis the account of Dunham&#x2019;s first time, and how her expectations of sex didn&#x2019;t quite live up to the actual event ((S2(BNo floodgate had been opened, no vault of true womanhood unlocked(S3(B); (S2(BGirls & Jerks(S3 (Bexplores her former attraction to less-than-nice guys&#x2014;guys who had perfected the (S2(Bdynamic of disrespect(S3 (Bshe found so intriguing; (S2(BIs This Even Real?(S3 (Bis a meditation on her lifelong obsession with death and dying&#x2014;what she calls her (S2(Bgenetically predestined morbidity.(S3 (BAnd in (S2(BI Didn&#x2019;t F*** Them, but They Yelled at Me,(S3 (Bshe imagines the tell-all she will write when she is eighty and past caring, able to reflect honestly on the sexism and condescension she has encountered in Hollywood, where women are (S2(Btreated like the paper thingies that protect glasses in hotel bathrooms&#x2014;necessary but infinitely disposable.(S3 (B&#xA0; Exuberant, moving, and keenly observed, Not That Kind of Girl is a series of dispatches from the frontlines of the struggle that is growing up. (S2(BI&#x2019;m already predicting my future shame at thinking I had anything to offer you,(S3 (BDunham writes. (S2(BBut if I can take what I&#x2019;ve learned and make one menial job easier for you, or prevent you from having the kind of sex where you feel you must keep your sneakers on in case you want to run away during the act, then every misstep of mine will have been worthwhile.(S3 (BPraise for Not That Kind of Girl &#xA0; (S2(BThe gifted Ms. Dunham not only writes with observant precision, but also brings a measure of perspective, nostalgia and an older person&#x2019;s sort of wisdom to her portrait of her (not all that much) younger self and her world. . . . As acute and heartfelt as it is funny.(S3(B&#x2014;Michiko Kakutani, The New York Times &#xA0; (S2(BIt&#x2019;s not Lena Dunham&#x2019;s candor that makes me gasp. Rather, it&#x2019;s her writing&#x2014;which is full of surprises where you least expect them. A fine, subversive book.(S3(B&#x2014;David Sedaris &#xA0; (S2(BThis book should be required reading for anyone who thinks they understand the experience of being a young woman in our culture. I thought I knew the author rather well, and I found many (not altogether welcome) surprises.(S3(B&#x2014;Carroll Dunham &#xA0; (S2(BWitty, illuminating, maddening, bracingly bleak . . . [Dunham] is a genuine artist, and a disturber of the order.(S3(B&#x2014;The Atlantic From the Trade Paperback edition.  aEssaysvForm  aPersonal MemoirsvBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY  aEntertainment & Performing ArtsvBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY 0aElectronic books.2 acloudLibrary403Whole productuhttp://ebook.yourcloudlibrary.com:80/library/dekrook-document_id-oczfp89423Front cover imageuhttp://images.yourcloudlibrary.com:80/delivery/img?type=DOCUMENTIMAGE&documentID=oczfp89&size=ORIGINAL02261nam  22002774  45000010014000000060019000140070015000330080041000480200018000890370012001070400028001190720023001471000026001702450048001962600036002443000011002805201342002915210017016336500028016506500030016786500018017086550022017267100017017488560092017658560126018579781250078421m    ||  d |      cr un|||||||||170506s2016||||||||||||s|||||||||||eng||  a9781250078421  aodhqar9  aMnSpTMCLbengcMnSpTMCL  aYAF0310002bisacsh1 aRusso, Meredith.4aut10aIf I Was Your Girlh[electronic resource] :  a[S.l.]:bFlatiron Books,c2016.  a272 p.  aThe award-winning, big-hearted novel about being seen for who you really are, and a love story you can't help but root for Amanda Hardy is the new girl in school. Like anyone else, all she wants is to make friends and fit in. But Amanda is keeping a secret, and she&#x2019;s determined not 